\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl480\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Once an employer has discharged their burden through offering accommodation, bilateral participation between employee and employer is required in determining what qualifies as reasonable accommodation. (THOMAS).  An employer, having presented a solution, it becomes the burden of the employee to then provide best efforts to resolve the dispute within that framework or to request alternatives in the event the employee can prove the accommodation does not provide the opportunity to resolve the issue. In }{\f2\fs28\b0\i0\ul\ulc0 Toledo v. Nobel-Sysco, Inc.}{\f2\fs28\b0\i0 , 892 F.2d 1481, 1486 (10th Cir. 1989), an employer unlawfully refused to hire the plaintiff due to his hearing impairment and only later offered a conditional accommodation. The court ultimately held the employer liable for the initial discriminatory refusal; however, it separately analyzed the interactive process and stressed that, once a reasonable accommodation is proposed, the employee must \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93make a good faith attempt to explore\u8221\'94 its possibilities and may not simply reject it outright without counterproposals or continued dialogue}
